h and recent expansion of theological studies, especially among conservative evangelical Christians, and sets the creation of British Columbia’s only department of religious studies at the University of British Columbia in this context. He also describes the innovative curricula designed by several of the institutions for the study of religion in the province. Finally, he contends that the differing views on the nature of religion held by these institutions and their constituencies have led to a continuing isolation from each other. The Study of Religion in British Columbia is the latest volume in the Canadian Corporation for the Study of Religion’s series on the study of religion in Canada. Readers interested in the rich diversity of personalities and perspectives that have shaped religious studies in British Columbia will find here a concise description of its evolution and a thought-provoking examination of its significance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReligionxStudy and teaching (Higher)zBritish Columbia. 0aReligionxStudy and teachingxBritish Columbia. 0aReligionxStudy and teachingzBritish Columbia. 0aTheologyxStudy and teaching (Higher)zBritish Columbia. 0aTheologyxStudy and teachingxBritish ColumbiaxBritish Columbia. 0aTheologyxStudy and teachingzBritish Columbia. 4aEducation. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Education.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920799840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207998/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Up